\begin_layout Remark
There are various holdup problems affected by the presence of non-competes
 that can be analyzed.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Investment by firm in manager's human capital
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Investment by manager in their own human capital
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Manager has no commitment power - contract must be incentive compatible.
 How to give manager incentive to invest in his human capital? Must give
 him some of the rent from that.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If we assume a contract – e.g., absence of non-competes – we can study what
 the effect is on investment.
 Here, we can 
\series bold
connect to the brain drain literaure 
\series default
because it is a similar tradeoff - the incumbent is like the developing
 country, its employee like a citizen, and not having non-competes is analogous
 allowing people to emigrate.
 Sure, you will get some brain drain from people leaving, but it also encourages
 their investment, and some stay (and in general, while they are here they
 have spillovers on others who are here)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Or we can try to figure out the optimal contract - I believe this is the
 subject of another paper, but not a dynamic contracting paper.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
What my model is about: Investment by firm in the knowledge they have in
 the first place.
 
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
The firm knows that in order to profit from this knowledge it will have
 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
