\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Remark
Try writing optimal contracting model where all that is chosen is length
 of non-compete and the buyout price - no buyout menu.
 What are some forces that could be in my model leading to non-competes
 being used in equilibrium? And further, what might make these outcomes
 socially inefficient, leading to a potential to want to regulate non-competes?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Remark

\series bold
The takeaway:
\series default
 allowing non-competes will only be constrained inefficient if they lead
 to the employer-employee pair solidifying their joint monopoly position
 in some capacity.
 However, 
\emph on
even then, 
\emph default
it may not be constrained inefficient: both because 
\series bold
monopoly power can have some surprising static constrained efficiency properties
\series default
 (for example, in R&D, less congestion); and
\series bold
 dynamic constrained efficiency properties
\series default
 because 
\series bold
static monopoly power
\series default
 increases appropriation of the rents from innovation, aligning more the
 incentive of innovators with the incentive of society
\series bold
 (they may increase inequality though)
\series default
.
 Of course, 
\series bold
monopoly power can also exhibit some dynamic inefficiency when it comes
 to R&D: 
\series default
to the extent that increasing quality leads firms to work their way down
 a demand curve, monopolistic firms will spend too little on R&D.
 Not sure how to think about whether / how these forces net out.
 I guess there is a chance that these offset each other and there is no
 way to reconcile them: if you give me monopoly power on both the idea and
 the research on the idea, then doing any might lower the price of the technolog
y sufficiently that none will happen anymore.
 The problem is that because the new idea displaces the old one, it is difficult
 to give a static monopoly without giving a dynamic monopoly.
 This adds to the tradeoff between increasing appropriability and static
 distortion.
 
\series bold
At the end of the day, non-competes, by creating a commitment device for
 the employee, 
\emph on
tend to increase bilateral value – 
\emph default
a good in and of itsel –
\emph on
 
\emph default
and tend to 
\emph on
increase the static and/or dynamic monopoly power
\emph default
 of the employer-employee pair, potentially bringing us closer or farther
 from this optimum.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Remark

\series bold
My paper: 
\series default
what is this additional monopoly power used for in my model? Since there
 is only one incumbent producing and his production decision is static,
\emph on
 
\series bold
\emph default
static monopoly power is unaffected.

\series default
 However, 
\series bold
dynamic monopoly power is affected: 
\series default
this power is used to avoid congestion in the R&D race (good for society).
 Not sure if the dynamic inefficiency int he previous paragraph is there.
 
\series bold
To make non-competes potentially socially inefficient, could work in monopsony
 power
\series default
: entrants not taking into account their effect on R&D wages, but for that
 need to have elastic supply of R&D labor.
 Not clear if there is a social inefficiency in my model.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Employee spinouts destroy the joint monopoly the two have on the knowledge.
 Optimal contract will feature a non-compete with a buyout clause that is
 too large to be worth buying out (because joint value is higher with no
 competition).
 Various ways:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Too much R&D effort.
 
\series bold
Do this first - it is the easiest.
 
\series default
This may be staticly socially efficient if 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

too much
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 means causes too much congestion in the race for ideas.
 But it may be staticly constrained inefficient if 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

too much
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 means hiring too many researchers, driving up the wage.
 On top of all of this, it may be 
\emph on
dynamically 
\emph default
socially inefficient if it eliminates the return 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Produce too much.
 Could be socially inefficient because we are talking about exploiting a
 demand curve.
 Or could be socially 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Employee risk aversion (assuming spinouts are bilaterally efficient) –>
 leads to non-competes being used, but no inefficiency.
 
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Optimal contract can no longer simply extract worker rent by paying lower
 wages, because the workers face idiosyncratic uncertainty: will they be
 the ones to get the idea? The firm does not perceive this uncertainty since
 it averages out for the firm.
 If workers are risk-averse enough, the knowledge will not be worth much
 to them initially, and it will cost too much to backload their wages by
 just giving them the promise of a potentially profitable spinout.
 Hence the optimal contract will involve the firm perfectly insuring the
 employee against such risk by taking all of the rent conditional on the
 worker spinning out, and paying the worker a higher wage today instead
 - i.e.
 a non-compete with a very large buyout.
 However, this would not be inefficient on its own: all spinouts are still
 forming, as is efficient.
 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Private information of employees and adverse selection.
 Various ways:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate

\emph on
At the time of spinning out: 
\emph default
if the employee, at the time of spinning out, has private information about
 the quality (but spinning out is always beneficial to joint value), then
 the firm will simply allow them to spin out and extract surplus through
 paying a lower wage.
 This is efficient.
 If spinning out is sometimes bad for joint value but good for employee
 value, then the firm may charge a buyout price that will screen these cases.
 Unfortunately, since there is not a perfect correlation between employee
 value and firm value, this will necessarily imply some loss.
 But it will be a loss to mutual value coming from the asymmetric information
 friction and moral hazard.
 As long as joint value is the same as social value (which we have assumed
 because we're not talking about case (1) here), this will still be constrained
 efficient from a social planner's perspective.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\emph on
At the time of hiring
\emph default
: suppose the employee has private information about his rate of acquiring
 ideas.
 Suppose the firm cannot make the worker sign a non-compete.
 The firm wants to extract rent from these workers, so it lowers the wage
 by 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta$
\end_inset

.
 But then only a few workers - who were basically worth hiring at 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta$
\end_inset

- are fired.
 If the conditions are right, the firm may optimally keep lowering the wage
 to the point that it employs no one.
 Enter non-competes.
 Now, the firm can simply require the workers to sign a non-compete and
 commit to extract the full rent in the event of a spinout (assuming all
 spinouts are bilaterally optimal).
 The firm is then free to hire the workers at the same wage.
 This feels like it would be socially optimal.
 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Moral hazard.
 Various ways:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
If workers can choose to put effort into becoming more productive vs learning
 to replicate, they may put more effort into learning to replicate than
 is mutually optimal (even if spining out is a net benefit) if they are
 not being charged a chunk of the benefit from spinning out (i.e.
 if there is no non-compete).
 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Section
Data and Calibration
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Directly, my model generates predictions about:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The wage 
\begin_inset Formula $w(\tilde{q},m)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The amount of innovation effort (hence R&D employment / spending) 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{I}(\tilde{q},m),z_{E}(\tilde{q},m),\tilde{z}_{E}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The growth rate, 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Unfortunately, I do not have data on 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{q}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 so I cannot use these predictions to calibrate the model as they are written.
 There are two ways to proceed:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Match marginal distributions such as the raw distribution of wages, innovations
 efforts, etc.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Add 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

labels
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 to the model that then can be used to match to the data.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
AK 2017 is an example of this.
 They construct a random process, the number of citations for a patent,
 that is a function of random processes already present in the model (and
 then doesn't feed back in), in a plausible way (larger innovations are
 more likely to be cited).
 This then generates a link between the model parameters and the citation
 distribution, which can be measured.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
In my case, there are a few ways to do this: 
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Let spinouts in the model correspond to spinouts in the data (if we can
 get this data), and let succesful entrants in the model (once knowledge
 required to participate in the product 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 race becomes publicly known) correspond to non-spinouts in the data.
 Then the fraction of new entrants that are spinouts (or, better yet, the
 distribution across businesses of their likelihood of generating spin-outs
 (but have to normalize by size)) becomes a moment that can discipline the
 model.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
However, there is a problem.
 There is much else that, in the data, generates wage dispersion.
 Thus, in order for this calibration to make sense, we really want to match
 the residual wage dispersion.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Model
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
[
\series bold
THIS POINT IS WELL UNDERSTOOD AND COVERED IN ACEMOGLU'S TEXTBOOK.]
\series default
 Akcigit & Kerr 2017 (AK) assume a representative agent and push all heterogenei
ty into heterogeneity of 
\emph on
firms 
\emph default
in their economy.
 Then the representative agent simply holds a portfolio of all firms in
 the economy.
 This is not quite microfounded in the sense that the agents should then
 have an incentive to instruct all of the firms to collude with each other,
 and hence each firm wouldn't be maximizing its own 
\emph on
individual 
\emph default
profit.
 In other words, creative destruction externalities would be internalized.
 So they have simply abstracted away from firm ownership, but continue to
 assume that individual firms maximize their own profits.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This trick works in AK because knowledge is embodied in the 
\emph on
firm
\emph default
.
 However, the whole point of my model is that workers have the knowledge,
 and worker flows are what is behind knowledge spillovers.
 Thus, I need to have knowledge embodied in workers.
 Each worker will have a set of intermediate goods that he is capable of
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

teaching
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 a firm how to produce.
 Therefore there will be a bunch of different wages and value functions
 to compute, it seems completely infeasible.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Preferences and Final Good Technology
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\series medium
There is a continuum of individuals indexed by 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in[0,1]$
\end_inset

.
 Each individual maximizes
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\series medium
AK uses log preferences, but I don't think it affects results (other than
 changing 
\begin_inset Formula $r=\rho$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $r=\rho+\dot{C}/C$
\end_inset

)
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U=\int_{0}^{\infty}\exp(-\rho t)C(t)dt
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Each individual is endowed with one unit of labor that it supplies to the
 market inelastically.
 Individuals have access to a short-term risk-free bond market, with exogenous
 interest rate 
\begin_inset Formula $r=\rho$
\end_inset

.
 Individuals can also form intermediate goods firms (described below).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Individuals consume a unique final good 
\begin_inset Formula $Y(t)$
\end_inset

.
 The final good is produced by labor and a continuum of intermediate goods
 
\begin_inset Formula $j\in[0,1]$
\end_inset

 with production technology
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Requiring labor input for the final good simplifies the computation of equilibri
um.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Y(t)=\frac{L^{\beta}(t)}{1-\beta}\int_{0}^{1}q_{j}^{\beta}(t)k_{j}^{1-\beta}(t)dj
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here, 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{j}(t)$
\end_inset

 is the quantity of the intermediate good 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $q(t)$
\end_inset

 is its quality.
 Normalize the price of the final good 
\begin_inset Formula $Y(t)$
\end_inset

 to be one in every period without loss of generality.
 The final good is produced competitively with input prices taken as given.
 From now on, the time index 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 will be supressed where it causes no confusion.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There is a
\series bold
 
\series default
unit mass of incument firms
\series bold
 
\series default
producing intermediate goods in equilibrium
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Don't know if it's necessary to talk about the measure 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 here.
 My best guess is that it 
\emph on
may 
\emph default
be helpful in dealing with labor market clearing, but I really don't understand
 the role of it to be honest.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 Each good 
\begin_inset Formula $j\in[0,1]$
\end_inset

 is produced with a linear technology, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
k_{j}=\overline{q}l_{j}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{q}$
\end_inset

 is the average quality level in the economy.
 Borrowing Assumption 1 from AK, only the leader in good 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 will produce good 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 at any given time.
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
This assumption implies that the price will be constant in 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

, but quantity sold will vary such that profit will scale with 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{j}$
\end_inset

.
 Alternatively, we could have assumed that 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{j}=q_{j}l_{j}$
\end_inset

.
 Then the CES demand structure would imply that 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{j}=\frac{w}{(1-\beta)q_{j}}$
\end_inset

.
 However, it would not necessarily imply that 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{j}=k$
\end_inset

 as in my 3rd year paper, since we have assumed that 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{j}^{\beta}$
\end_inset

, rather than 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{j}$
\end_inset

, enters the final good production function.
 Look into this eventually, it doesn't seem like an important detail.
 In both cases the growth rate of the economy is just the growth rate of
 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{q}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Individuals can supply labor in three capacities: final good production
 (
\begin_inset Formula $L^{F}$
\end_inset

), intermediate good production (
\begin_inset Formula $L^{I}$
\end_inset

), and R&D (
\begin_inset Formula $L^{RD}$
\end_inset

).
 The labor market satisfies 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
L_{t}^{F}+L_{t}^{I}+L_{t}^{RD}\le1
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There is no goods market clearing condition because agents can borrow from
 abroad 
\series bold
[UNDERSTAND THIS].
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Research & Development
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Incumbent R&D
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Incumbent firms undertake R&D to improve the quality of the product they
 sell.
 A successful R&D project on product 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 of quality 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 renders its owner an incumbent producing product 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 with quality 
\begin_inset Formula $(1+\lambda)q_{j}$
\end_inset

.
 Define 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{z}=\int_{0}^{m_{j}}z_{l}dl+z_{I}$
\end_inset

 as the total innovation effort undertaken on product 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

.
 Innovation effort 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 requires 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 units of R&D labor, and generates innovations at rate
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
R_{I}(z;\overline{z})=\chi_{I}z\phi(\overline{z})
\]

\end_inset

To capture the net effect of all congestion and agglomeration externalities,
 we introduce the function 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 of total innovation effort.
 In general this could have any form to reflect these externalities; here,
 to keep the model simple, we assume 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 is decreasing, with 
\begin_inset Formula $\lim_{z\to0}\phi(z)=+\infty$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\lim_{z\to\infty}\phi(z)=0$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, let 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(\overline{z})=\overline{z}^{\psi-1}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi<1.$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Entrant R&D
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The R&D technology for entrants differs only in the constant 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi_{E}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
This constant is only introduced to increase the quantitative flexibility
 of the model.
 Even with 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi_{E}=\chi_{I}$
\end_inset

, incumbents invest in R&D effort when there are no entrants (due to 
\begin_inset Formula $\lim_{z\to0}\phi(z)=+\infty$
\end_inset

), and eventually stop innovation effort as more and more R&D startups are
 formed.
 (This is another prediction of my model which could be used to discipline
 the model).
 
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
R_{E}(z;\overline{z})=\chi_{E}z\phi(\overline{z})
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that entrants are 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

small
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and do not take into account their effect on decreasing returns to R&D
 in the sector.
 To pin down the size of an individual entrant, assume that each startup
 can hire at most 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi>0$
\end_inset

 units of R&D labor.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{z}=\int_{0}^{m_{j}}z_{l}dl+z_{I}=\xi m_{j}+z_{I}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Finally, when the R&D technology becomes public, entry occurs until 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{j}$
\end_inset

 reaches the value 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{t}(q)$
\end_inset

 at which entrants make zero profits in expectation.
 It can be shown that 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Knowledge spillovers
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Details
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
[ADD SPILLOVERS FROM ENTRANTS EMPLOYING R&D WORKERS AS WELL, IF POSSIBLE.
 COULD EVEN HAVE DIFF ABILITY TO ENFORCE NONCOMPETES]
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An individual who supplies 
\begin_inset Formula $l_{j}$
\end_inset

 units of R&D labor to either an incumbent producing machine line 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 of quality 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 (to invent quality 
\begin_inset Formula $(1+\lambda)q$
\end_inset

) – or a spin-out competing with this incumbent to invent 
\begin_inset Formula $(1+\lambda)q$
\end_inset

 – acquires the ability to 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

spin-off
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and compete in thee R&D race at an instantaneous Poisson rate 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu l_{j}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Making spillovers a function of R&D employment, not total employment, both
 (1) makes sense intuitively, and (2) keeps the intermediate goods firms'
 
\emph on
good output 
\emph default
decision simple and static, simplifying the model significantly.
 Of course, their R&D decision will now be distorted by the effect of employment
 on knowledge leaks.
 But this is the kind of result we want in the model - spin-outs distorting
 R&D and growth.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Why perform R&D instead of simply forming a competitor of the incumbent
 producing the machine of quality 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{j}$
\end_inset

? We can assume they learn how to make machine 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{j}$
\end_inset

 and still preserve this behavior by adding something analogoous to Assumption
 1 here as well.
 If any spin-out has to pay a small cost to play, and we assume that competition
 
\emph on
within 
\emph default
machine line is Bertrand (why? why not?), then no one will spin-out until
 they discover a truly superior quality product.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset

 I conjecture that as soon as an individual acquires this knowledge, they
 will switch their R&D labor supply to a different machine line, since the
 wage will be pushed down by workers willing to work for less in order to
 acquire this knowledge.
 This means that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\dot{m}_{j}=\nu\hat{l}_{j}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{l}_{j}$
\end_inset

 is the amount of labor used for R&D in sector 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Non-competes
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the version of the model with non-competes, workers will be unable to
 spin-out until 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{c}$
\end_inset

 years after leaving employment at their employer.
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
For tractability, will actually assume a Poisson process 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

shocks
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 the workers out of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

employment restricted
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 status.
 Calibrate this shock so that the average non-compete is 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{c}$
\end_inset

 years long.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset

 During this time, the worker can work in any other industry but not the
 industry he was previously working at.
 However, there is a significant probability that the knowledge will become
 fully public, reducing the payoff to potentially attaining knowledge.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Equilibrium
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Production
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
[
\series bold
FIX HJBS TO TAKE INTO ACCOUNT NEW R&D FUNCTION 
\series default
- see stuff in notebook about finding the root of the FOC, need to use numeric
 method, but looks like objective is monotonic so can simply do binary search
 to find the zero]
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 denote the (exogenous) rate at which knowledge enters the public domain
 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{z}_{E}^{t}(q_{j},m_{j})$
\end_inset

 denote the (endogenous) rate at which a new spinoff is formed in product
 line 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 of quality 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 at time 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

, given the efforts of the mass 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{j}$
\end_inset

 of potential entrants.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{t}(q_{j})$
\end_inset

 denote the time-
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 flow profit to an incumbent with quality 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{j}$
\end_inset

 (given optimal monopolistic competition pricing).
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{t}(q_{j},m_{j})$
\end_inset

 denote the time-
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 value of a frontier firm producing a good of quality 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{j}$
\end_inset

 and mass 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{j}$
\end_inset

 of potential entrants
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
In general, 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{t}$
\end_inset

 would also depend on 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

.
 However, 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 only affects the value through 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{j}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{j}$
\end_inset

 so we can drop the 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 superscript on 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and write simply 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{t}(q,m)$
\end_inset

.
 Later, we will normalize by the average quality level in the economy and
 show that 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{t}(q,m)=Q_{t}A(q/Q_{t},m)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{t}(q,m)$
\end_inset

 satisfies the HJB 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\big(r+\theta+\tau_{t}(q,m)\big)A_{t}(q,m) & = & \max_{z}\pi_{t}(q)+\theta B_{t}(q)+z\phi(z+\overline{z}_{E})\Big[A_{t}((1+\lambda)q,0)-A_{t}(q,m)\Big]\\
 &  & +\nu(\overline{z}_{E}(q,m)+z)\partial_{m}A_{t}(q,m)-w_{t}(q,m)z+\partial_{t}A_{t}(q,m)
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{t}(q_{j})$
\end_inset

 denote the (endogenous) rate at which startups are formed once knowledge
 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{j}$
\end_inset

 is in the public domain.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{t}(q_{j})$
\end_inset

 denote the time-
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 value of a quality 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{j}$
\end_inset

 frontier firm whose knowledge has entered the public domain.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{t}$
\end_inset

 denote the wage paid to R&D labor when the knowledge has entered the public
 domain (this will be equal to the final goods wage in equilibrium, due
 to indifference condition).
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{t}(q)$
\end_inset

 satisfies the HJB 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\big(r+\sigma_{t}(q)\big)B_{t}(q)=\pi_{t}(q)+\partial_{t}B_{t}(q)+\max_{z}z\phi(\overline{z}_{E}+z)[A_{t}((1+\lambda)q,0)-B_{t}(q)]-w_{t}z
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Maximization in the final goods sector and by the producers yields (see
 AK) 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
w_{t}=\tilde{\beta}\overline{q}_{t}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\tilde{\beta}\equiv\beta^{\beta}[1-\beta]^{1-2\beta}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Individuals
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Because individuals simply maximize the present-value of their consumption,
 and because their wages from supplying labor do not depend on their entrepreneu
rial efforts, we can simply think of the behavior of individuals as resulting
 from the separate maximization of the utilization of their various forms
 of capital: their time and their knowledge.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Individuals supply labor to production of the intermediate goods as well
 as to R&D.
 Therefore, the flow value that a worker receives from R&D employment must
 be equal to the wage rate for intermediate goods production,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
w_{t}=\tilde{\beta}\overline{q}_{t}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Spin-outs
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $W_{t}^{NC}(q,m)$
\end_inset

 denote the value to an individual of having acquired the technology to
 form a spin-out in a machine line of current quality 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 and mass of competing entrants 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

, but bound by a non-compete agreement.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $W_{t}^{F}(q,m)$
\end_inset

 denote the value to an individual once the non-compete has expired (
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Free-agent
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

).
 Individuals flow out of competition restriction at instantaneous Poisson
 rate 
\begin_inset Formula $v=1/T_{c}$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
This ensures that the average length of a non-compete is 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{c}$
\end_inset

 years.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Recall that ideas enter the public domain at rate 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 and are improved upon at rate 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{t}(q,m)$
\end_inset

.
 In both of these events, the value to an individual with the technology
 goes to zero: in the former case, due to free entry; in the latter case,
 due to Assumption 1.
 Further, recall that 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{m}$
\end_inset

 is proportional to 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{L}_{j}$
\end_inset

, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{L}_{t}(q,m)$
\end_inset

 denote the equilibrium labor allocation.
 Therefore, 
\begin_inset Formula $W_{t}^{NC}(q,m)$
\end_inset

 satisfies the HJB 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(r+\theta+\tau_{t}(q,m)+v)W_{t}^{NC}(q,m)=vW_{t}^{F}(q,m)+\partial_{m}W_{t}^{NC}(q,m)\hat{L}_{t}(q,m)+\partial_{t}W_{t}^{NC}(q,m)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I assume that R&D workers employed by spin-outs learn at the same rate as
 those employed by incumbents.
 Therefore they earn the same wage 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{t}(q,m)$
\end_inset

 whether employed by incumbents or spin-outs.
 Therefore, 
\begin_inset Formula $W_{t}^{F}(q,m)$
\end_inset

 satisfies the HJB 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\big(r+\theta+\tau_{t}(q,m)\big)W_{t}^{F}(q,m) & = & \max_{z}\Big\{ z\big[A_{t}((1+\lambda)q,0)-W_{t}^{F}(q,m)\big]-w_{t}(q,m)R_{E}(z)\Big\}\\
 &  & +\partial_{m}W_{t}^{F}(q,m)\nu(\hat{L}_{t}(q,m)+mL_{t}^{E}(q,m))+\partial_{t}W_{t}^{F}(q,m)
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
and 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{E}(q,m)$
\end_inset

 is the argmax.
 Note that, in contrast with the incumbent, individual spin-out does not
 take into account the effect of its level of employment on the spillovers
 of knowledge.
 This is because each individual spin-out is infinitesimal relative to the
 entire mass of spin-outs or to the mass of the incumbent.
 
\series bold
[make sure this makes sense].
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The effective flow wage received by a worker, including the flow value of
 the possibility of acquiring valuable knowledge, is given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
w(q,m)+\nu W_{t}^{NC}(q,m)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Due to Inada conditions on the R&D technology, we know we will have an interior
 solution.
 Therefore workers must be indifferent between supplying R&D to each type,
 and hence 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
w_{t}(q,m)+\nu W_{t}^{NC}(q,m)=\tilde{\beta}\overline{q}_{t}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
BGP
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{q}=q/\overline{q}.$
\end_inset

 In this section, I look for a balanced growth path with a stationary joint
 distribution of 
\begin_inset Formula $(\tilde{q},m)$
\end_inset

; where policies are functions of 
\begin_inset Formula $(\tilde{q},m)$
\end_inset

 and invariant over time
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Hence so are endogenous variables such as 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{t}(q,m)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

; and where 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

, wages, and value functions all grow at exponential rate 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
First, recall that 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{t}(q)=\pi q$
\end_inset

.
 Suppose we are on a BGP with growth rate 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{t}(q)=e^{gt}\tilde{B}(\tilde{q})$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\partial_{t}e^{gt}\tilde{B}(e^{-gt}q)=ge^{gt}\tilde{B}(\tilde{q})-ge^{gt}\tilde{q}\tilde{B}'(\tilde{q})
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
and the HJB becomes, after dividing by 
\begin_inset Formula $e^{gt}$
\end_inset

 and rearranging,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\overbrace{(r+\sigma(\tilde{q})-g)}^{\text{Effective discount factor}}\tilde{B}(\tilde{q}) & = & \underbrace{\pi\tilde{q}}_{\text{Flow profits}}-\underbrace{g\tilde{q}\tilde{B}'(\tilde{q})}_{\text{Obsolescence}}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Next, suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{t}(q,m)=e^{gt}\tilde{A}(\tilde{q},m)$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\partial_{t}e^{gt}\tilde{A}(\tilde{q},m)]=ge^{gt}\tilde{A}(\tilde{q},m)-ge^{gt}\tilde{q}\partial_{q}\tilde{A}(\tilde{q},m)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
and the HJB becomes
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\big(r+\theta+\tau(\tilde{q},m)-g\big)\tilde{A}(\tilde{q},m) & = & \overbrace{\pi\tilde{q}}^{\text{Flow profit}}+\overbrace{\theta\tilde{B}(\tilde{q})}^{\text{Knowledge becomes public}}-\overbrace{g\tilde{q}\partial_{q}\tilde{A}(\tilde{q},m)}^{\text{Obsolescence}}\\
 &  & +\max_{z}\Big\{\underbrace{z\big[\tilde{A}((1+\lambda)\tilde{q},0)-\tilde{A}(\tilde{q},m)\big]}_{\text{Expected flow capital gain from R\&D}}\\
 &  & +\underbrace{\partial_{m}\tilde{A}(\tilde{q},m)(\nu R_{I}(z)+L_{E}^{R}(\tilde{q},m))}_{\text{Knowledge spillover cost of R\&D}}-\underbrace{w(\tilde{q},m)R_{I}(z)}_{\text{Direct cost of R\&D}}\Big\}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Next, consider the value function 
\begin_inset Formula $W_{t}^{NC}(q,m),W_{t}^{F}(q,m).$
\end_inset

 Supposing 
\begin_inset Formula $W_{t}^{NC}(q,m)=e^{gt}\tilde{W}^{NC}(\tilde{q},m)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $W_{t}^{F}(q,m)=e^{gt}\tilde{W}^{F}(\tilde{q},m)$
\end_inset

, have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\partial_{t}[e^{gt}W^{NC}(e^{-gt}q,m)] & = & ge^{gt}W^{NC}(e^{-gt}q,m)-ge^{gt}\tilde{q}\partial_{\tilde{q}}W^{NC}(e^{-gt}q,m)\\
\partial_{t}[e^{gt}W^{F}(e^{-gt}q,m)] & = & ge^{gt}W^{F}(e^{-gt}q,m)-ge^{gt}\tilde{q}\partial_{\tilde{q}}W^{F}(e^{-gt}q,m)
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The HJBs become
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
(r+\theta+\tau(\tilde{q},m)+v-g)\tilde{W}^{NC}(\tilde{q},m) & = & \overbrace{v\tilde{W}^{F}(\tilde{q},m)}^{\text{Expiry of non-compete}}+\overbrace{\partial_{m}\tilde{W}^{NC}(\tilde{q},m)\nu L^{R}(\tilde{q},m)}^{\text{Loss of rents due to knowledge spillovers}}\\
 &  & -\underbrace{g\tilde{q}\partial_{\tilde{q}}\tilde{W}^{NC}(\tilde{q},m)}_{\text{Obsolescence}}\\
(r+\theta+\tau(\tilde{q},m)-g)\tilde{W}^{F}(\tilde{q},m) & = & \overbrace{\max_{z}\Big\{ z\big[\tilde{A}((1+\lambda)\tilde{q},0)-\tilde{W}^{F}(\tilde{q},m)\big]-w(\tilde{q},m)R_{E}(z)\Big\}}^{\text{(Net) flow value from R\&D}}\\
 &  & +\underbrace{\partial_{m}\tilde{W}^{F}(\tilde{q},m)\nu(z+L_{E}^{R}(\tilde{q},m)}_{\text{Loss of rents due to knowledge spillovers}}-\underbrace{g\tilde{q}\partial_{\tilde{q}}\tilde{W}^{F}(\tilde{q},m)}_{\text{Obsolescence}}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Stationary joint distribution of 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
On the BGP, there is a stationary distribution over 
\begin_inset Formula $(\log(q/\overline{q}),m,n)$
\end_inset

.
 For a firm at 
\begin_inset Formula $(q/\overline{q},m,n)$
\end_inset

, we can write the evolution of 
\begin_inset Formula $\log(q/\overline{q})$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
d\log(q/\overline{q}) & = & d\log(q)-d\log(\overline{q})\\
 & = & p(\tilde{q},m,n)dN_{t}-gdt
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{t}$
\end_inset

 is the process recording the number of Poisson arrivals, so 
\begin_inset Formula $dN_{t}=1$
\end_inset

 if there is an arrival, 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 otherwise; and 
\begin_inset Formula $p(\tilde{q},m,n)$
\end_inset

 is the equilibrium intensity of innovation arrivals to a firm at 
\begin_inset Formula $(\tilde{q,}m,n)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In equilibrium, 
\begin_inset Formula $(m,n)$
\end_inset

 simply drift through the state space:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
dn & = & (\nu\tau(\tilde{q},m,n)-vn)dt\\
dm & = & vndt
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi(\tilde{q},m,n,t)$
\end_inset

 denote the density of firms in state 
\begin_inset Formula $(\tilde{q},m,n)$
\end_inset

 at time 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

.
 This function satisfies the Kolmogorov Forward equation 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\psi_{t} & = & g\psi_{q}+vn\psi_{m}-(\nu\tau(\tilde{q},m,n)-vn)\psi_{n}\\
 &  & +\mathbb{E}_{m',n'}\Big[p(q-(1+\lambda),m',n')\psi(q-(1+\lambda),m',n')\Big]
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Quantitative Analysis
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Computer Algorithm 1 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I solve the model as a fixed point over 
\begin_inset Formula $g,L^{F},\overline{z}_{E}(\tilde{q},m),\overline{z}_{E}^{0}(\tilde{q})$
\end_inset

.
 [MAY NEED TO ADD ANOTHER aggregate variable, 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{E}(\tilde{q},m)$
\end_inset

 because it affects rate of drift in 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 direction].
 The computational loop has the following steps:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Guess 
\begin_inset Formula $g,L^{F},\overline{z}_{E}(\tilde{q},m),\overline{z}_{E}^{0}(\tilde{q})$
\end_inset

.
 Compute 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(\tilde{q})=\pi\tilde{q}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi=\pi(L^{F};\text{parameters})$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Solve for 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{I}^{A}(\tilde{q},m),A(\tilde{q},m),z_{I}^{B}(\tilde{q}),B(\tilde{q})$
\end_inset

 using 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(\tilde{q})$
\end_inset

 and other guesses.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Solve for 
\begin_inset Formula $A,B$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{I}^{A},z_{I}^{B}$
\end_inset

 by policy function iteration method used in Kaplan & Moll's HACT papers.
 Do we think such a fixed point exists? Yes: we are essentially solving
 for the value of how much a firm would want to invest if creative destruction
 were exogenous and given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau(\tilde{q},m)$
\end_inset

 and wages were exogenous and given by 
\begin_inset Formula $w(\tilde{q},m)$
\end_inset

.
 This is a well-defined problem which has the HJB, so no reason to think
 it won't converge.
 
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Finding 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{I}^{A}(\tilde{q},m)$
\end_inset

 is harder with the new setup - there is no explicit expression for it.
 However, we can use some method to find a solution to the FOC.
 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Solve individual entrant problems: compute 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{E}(\tilde{q},m)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{E}^{0}(\tilde{q})$
\end_inset

 given 
\begin_inset Formula $A(\tilde{q},0)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Given assumptions, we will have 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{E}(\tilde{q},m)=\xi$
\end_inset

 as long as 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Set 
\begin_inset Formula $F=\overline{z}_{E}^{0}(\tilde{q})/z_{E}(\tilde{q},m)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Check consistency of aggregate variables 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau(\tilde{q},m),\sigma(\tilde{q}),w(\tilde{q},m)$
\end_inset

 by updating to new 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau,\sigma$
\end_inset

 values according to (defining 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{z}(\tilde{q},m)=z_{E}(\tilde{q},m)+z_{I}(\tilde{q},m)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{z}_{E}(\tilde{q},m)=\min(m(\tilde{q}),m\xi)$
\end_inset

):
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Check consistency of 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau(\tilde{q},m)=\big(\chi_{I}z_{I}(\tilde{q},m)+\chi_{E}z_{E}(\tilde{q},m)\big)\phi(\overline{z}(\tilde{q},m))$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Public domain free-entry condition: 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{z}_{E}A((1+\lambda)\tilde{q},0)=wR_{E}(\tilde{z}_{E},\tilde{q})=w\tilde{z}_{E}\phi(F\tilde{z}_{E})$
\end_inset

, which becomes 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A((1+\lambda)\tilde{q},0)=w\phi(F\tilde{z}_{E})
\]

\end_inset

(guaranteed to hold for some 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{z}_{E}$
\end_inset

, and same 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{z}_{E}$
\end_inset

 for each 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{q}$
\end_inset

 as well) and set 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma^{+}=F\tilde{z}_{E}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
R&D labor indifference condition: 
\begin_inset Formula $w(\tilde{q},m)=\tilde{\beta}-\nu\tilde{A}((1+\lambda)\tilde{q},m)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
If not converged, go to step (1ai) with new guesses for these aggregate
 variables.
 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Given 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau,\sigma,z_{I}(\tilde{q},m)$
\end_inset

, compute stationary joint distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu(q,m)$
\end_inset

.
 Two ways to do this:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Solve Kolmogorov Forward partial differential equation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Simulate the economy for many periods starting with some initial distribution
 and policy rules computed above, and then numerically approximate the resulting
 distribution (probably easier).
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Update growth rate using 
\begin_inset Formula $g=\lambda(\int_{0}^{\infty}\sigma(q)\mu(q,0)dq+\int_{0}^{\infty}\tau(q,m)\mu(q,m)dqdm$
\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If not converged, go to step (2).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Finally, check labor market clearing: 
\begin_inset Formula $L^{F}+L^{I}(L^{F})+L^{RD}(L^{F})=1$
\end_inset

.
 If excess demand for labor, lower 
\begin_inset Formula $L^{F}$
\end_inset

 and return to step 1.
 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Subsection
Computer Algorithm 2
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Guess a growth rate 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Guess an R&D labor allocation, 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{L}(q,m)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Section
Welfare
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Is there even an inefficiency in my model without non-competes? I.e.
 is there any potential role for them in the optimal policy from a social
 perspective? (Different question than whether they will be used bilaterally
 and what the effects of this are, but it answers pretty clearly that you
 should prohibit them, becasue regardless, you would want to).
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Not that clear.
 The FOC for incumbents is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
w(q,m,n)=(\phi(\tau)+z\phi'(\tau))\Big[A((1+\lambda)q,0,0)-A(q,m,n)\Big]
\]

\end_inset

which in the decentralized equilibrium, usign 
\begin_inset Formula $w(q,m,n)=\overline{w}-\nu W^{NC}(q,m,n)$
\end_inset

 and rearranging, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\overline{w} & = & (\phi(\tau)+z\phi'(\tau))\Big[A((1+\lambda)q,0,0)-A(q,m,n)\Big]\\
 &  & +\nu W^{NC}(q,m,n)
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The LHS is the marginal opportunity cost of using labor in R&D in terms
 of lost final good consumption, since 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{w}$
\end_inset

 is its marginal product in producing the final good.
 The RHS is marginal benefit to the incumbent of additional R&D, plus the
 expected marginal benefit to the employee.
 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
We can set up the actual optimization problem following the methods used
 in Liyan's article.
 The planner's problem is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\max\int_{0}^{\infty}e^{-\rho t}C_{t}dt
\]

\end_inset

subject to 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
C_{t} & = & \frac{L^{\beta}}{1-\beta}\int_{0}^{1}q_{j}^{\beta}k_{j}^{1-\beta}dj\\
k_{j} & = & \overline{q}l_{j}\\
\overline{q}_{t} & = & \int_{0}^{1}q_{t}^{j}dj\\
\frac{d\overline{q}_{t}}{\overline{q}_{t}} & = & \Bigg(\int(q/\overline{q}_{t})\tau(q,m,n,t)\phi(\tau(q,m,n,t))d\psi(q,m,n,t)\Bigg)dt
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Key tradeoff in my model: when someone obtains a monopoly, they may not
 innovate on their technology at the socially optimal rate because they
 do not internalize the fact that one day someone else may use this knowledge
 without their explicit consent (hence no bargaining, hence pareto suboptimal).
 To the extent that this is the case, it is a Pareto improvement to increase
 the amount of R&D.
 One way to accomplish this is through increasing the rate of knowledge
 spillovers, which leads to R&D by new entrants.
 While these entrants also do not take into account their effect on future
 users of the knowledge they are creating, they have another offsetting
 bias towards too much innovation stemming from the business-stealing effect
 of their innovation.
 Hence, more entry can lead to a Pareto improvement.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
This leaves out an important effect of relaxing the ownership of intellectual
 property: there could be some match-specific productivity, i.e.
 some people are more effective than others with a given piece of knowledge.
 Here it is useful to compare the case of patents to the case of IP that
 for some reason or another cannot be enforced by a patent (this has to
 be what my model is about - have a good answer for why this might be the
 case!).
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
If I patent some knowledge, it becomes like any other asset: I can simply
 sell the patent to the highest bidder and in equilibrium it will go to
 (and be priced by) the agent with the best (private) use of the asset.
 This person may then produce a suboptimally low quantity of output with
 this idea because of his monopoly power, c.f.
 above.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Without patents, the inventor cannot use the market mechanism to sell the
 knowledge to the appropriate person, for two reasons: (1) he has no mechanism
 for credibly communicating to the other agents the nature of the knowledge
 (and hence its value to them) because anyone can use the knowledge once
 they see it; and (2) even if somehow someone knew the value of the knowledge,
 the inventor cannot commit to not using the knowledge once it is 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

sold
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 to the buyer, hence the buyer will not be willing to pay a price high enough
 to offset the destruction of the inventor's current monopoly, and the knowledge
 trade will not take place.
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Most non-enforcing states, including California, allow VC firms to require
 employees at the firsm they fund to sign non-competes as a condition of
 their investment.
 This suggests an alternative path for an inventor in a non-enforcing region
 who has some IP he does not want to patent for whatever reason: form a
 firm with the knowledge embodied in the firm, sell it to a VC or other
 investor, and sign a non-compete.
 If anything, this is good for my paper, because it suggests that 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

knowledge finding the right people
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 is not as big a problem in non-enforcing regions (while the monopoly underinves
tment in R&D, which is in my model, may still be).
 A caveat: many would say that VC firms are not the people who we are trying
 to match with knowledge.
 What we really want is smart people in their basements who have some kind
 of brilliant way of thinking, but don't have access to this seed of knowledge
 currently possessed by the inventor.
 Financial frictions prevent them from accessing this knowledge.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Having non-competes is like granting inventors 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

patents
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 on their inventions, 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Everything above has been about 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

does having non-competes increase or decrease welfare
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 But this is not quite the same as asking 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

does 
\emph on
enforcing 
\emph default
non-competes increase or decrease welfare
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 because we have not required that non-compete contracts 
\end_layout

